            <p>Vaughan has many private schools. After divorce, which school a child attends and who pays the fees often becomes a major dispute. Miao He helps incorporate these specifics — school choice, extracurricular activities, and fee allocation — into a formal Parenting Plan, giving these arrangements legal enforceability.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2>Protecting Parental Gifts &amp; Family Property</h2>
            <p>It is common in Vaughan's Chinese-Canadian community for parents to purchase a home for their child. A Marriage Contract can clearly specify that such property is a pre-marital gift and is excluded from Equalization — protecting generational family wealth. The contract must be reviewed by independent counsel for each party to be enforceable.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2>Cross-Border Asset Recovery</h2>
            <p>Vaughan Chinese-Canadian families frequently hold Chinese real estate, bank deposits, or company shares. Miao He's dual Ontario-China licence allows her to handle cross-border asset disclosure, valuation, and recovery directly. She has successfully helped clients recover <strong>over $300,000 CAD</strong> in cross-border hidden assets.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Question</h2>
            <p class="faq-q">My parents bought our Vaughan home for us. Can my spouse take half in a divorce?</p>
            <p>It depends on registration and documentation. If the property was a gift to you alone — not to both spouses — and this is clearly documented, it may be excluded from Equalization. Miao He has handled many cases involving parental property in Vaughan and can assess your specific situation directly.</p>
